Foodstuffs to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation measured in the euro area was the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 euro-zone countries, inflation was higher than expected in November - after the 2.6% in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1% was recorded, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts have been based on only 3 percent, reported Bloomberg.
In contrast to the US, British, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the central rate and, in its discretion, the interest rate reduction would encourage the rise in commodity prices and the slight fall in unemployment to create an inflation spiral.
The ECB is committed to keeping the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in the process of being "agreed" on inflation in order to avoid the need for later action.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate in Germany reached a record 12-year high in November; in Spain, the rate increased from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The rise in inflation in the euro-zone was responsible for the increased food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat quotations increased by 88 percent and the price for soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in food oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil increased by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached almost US $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but it is expected to fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3% inflation rate, but the average annual rate is 2.1%.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to reduce interest rates twice.
