Saving many places on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to an improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in hospitals, the overloading of beds, the overload of staff - all factors that are not very conducive to the containment of the infections, says the leading doctor of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many places, the disinfectants are also saved.
In the trauma department of the János hospital, an MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed.
The bacterium resistant to antibiotics was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was a similar infection.
The injured person in a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation has not been carried out since then because of the bacteria still in the patient's body.
Until 10 December of this year, infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens from hospitals were reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to the leading doctor of the National Epidemiology Centre, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been registered in hospitals, but the dark rate is likely to be higher.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by the MRSA, the Staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of the people in their nose without it causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as throat inflammation, almond inflammation, skin inflammation or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well-curable.
However, if the means are used too high or incorrectly, the well-responding bacteria produce antibiotic-resistant, which rapidly spread in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
These bacteria may cause severe infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis, especially in patients with a weakened, or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in elderly, or low body weight patients.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such events are part of the day-to-day disease.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA only did not exist where it was not sought.
Resistance to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the caregivers wear rubber gloves and masks in the supply, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - said Tibor Nyulasi.
When they are admitted to the hospital, patients are examined for MRSA, but an infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rare
The majority of the infections in hospitals caused by MRSA would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable for the control of the development or spread of the multi-resistant agent, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and old-age homes, the hospitals should examine the patients who have been given it and immediately isolate MRSA-infected patients.
In the Hungarian hospitals, however, the microbiological sample collection is not used so often.
Not least because there are no grants from the State Health Insurance Fund for this investigation.
Most cases would therefore only come to light when the patient already has a remarkable MRSA infection, the medical director of the Epidemiology Centre said.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotherapy should be targeted, i.e., microbiological studies are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug, but this directive is not always respected by hospitals.
Among the outpatient, or in basic care, microbiological sampling is even less rare, says Karolina Böröcz.
Saving the disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is the most frequently transmitted by the care staff from one patient to the other.
This is why the washing of hands, or the wearing of gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplets infection or contact, but there is not always the possibility of isolating the infected patient in the local hospitals.
The rooms are even often overcrowded, the beds are close to each other, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, in the financially less well-placed hospitals it even happens that there is a saving on disinfectants, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that really favour the development of infections.
Such infections are shown to be far less common there, or can be stopped the further spread of the pathogen, where these protective measures are being observed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
To get to grips with MRSA infections causes enormous costs for health insurance, so they are being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was included in the government programme.
According to the first signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the tendency of MRSA infections in England is decreasing.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
