Fodor and the six Hungarian progeny
As Minister of the Environment Gábor Fodor announced, the meeting of experts will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the post-2012 emission reduction measures, i.e. after the end of the Kyoto Protocol.
A strong debate is under way between developed and developing countries.
The US has already indicated that they do not want to negotiate on concrete figures, but they would be ready to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40% by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major question of the conference is whether the developed countries are prepared to support developing countries in addition to the reduction of emissions, both financially and technologically.
An agreement on support for developing countries has also been reached.
The adaptation fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, probably at the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be seen in the "Piac és Profit."
Hungary's six percent
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that the EU will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (in terms of 1990 levels), whether or not the "post-2012 agreement" will be successful, and that the Union would even be prepared to work for a 30% reduction, if other major industrial countries in the world, or developing countries are also prepared to meet their commitments in a strong and responsible manner.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the objective of the States that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2%, while the EU, with its then 15 member states, had already committed itself to a reduction of 8%.
The target for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to the years 1985-87 - a target that the country will meet, as can be seen in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The use is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly only come into force after 2012. In this case, the reduction projects set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new, international emission reduction system, the importance of which has also been highlighted by the IPCC, the international scientific climate change committee of the UN in its recent report, which is excellent with the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would delay the reduction of emissions and the increase of the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 ° C would be inevitable, which, according to scientists, would have very serious and irreparable consequences.
British Army Protests on YouTube
British Army units have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase their popularity on the video portal.
First of all, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Special Units stationed in Afghanistan have been loading videos of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, reports the BBC.
The images, which are shot with a camera on helmets, are controlled at the air-force base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are placed on the Internet.
Political message inevitable
Air force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in spring 2007 under the "defenceheadquarters" to publish videos on Iraqi and Afghan operations, as well as the British Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Commonwealth Office) and the international peace forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq have their own YouTube channels.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force has released the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defence says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the people about the actual objectives of the foreign operations.
Such published propaganda is almost free of charge compared to conventional TV advertising, said defence expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message in themselves, as they confirm the existence of the military measures adopted by the government in their own way.
American advertise with game
The army, however, must also fight against amateur recordings, which, in addition to the carefully worked, censored recordings, also make it into the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: in the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the most important is the loss, but the bloody side of the war is not shown.
By the way, many videos of the war scene in Iraq and Afghanistan have already been loaded to the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this "genus."
The Americans, however, are advertising in a somewhat different way, with the free-of-charge shooting game "America's Army," in which the player can slip into the soldier's skin as part of a more or less life-wide simulation.
