Public holidays are not always public holidays
In Hungary, public holidays are regulated by law, so that the practice of redisposing of working days around the public holidays has now established, but the coming year will give us less such days.
In the EU and in America, too, there is something else called "holiday."
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and free days.
Working-free days are mostly church holidays, or are related to important historical events.
For example, we are celebrating New Year's Eve: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are free days - the latter alone so that the New Year's celebrations can rest.
All year round, we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The state holidays are the 15th of March, which is reminiscent of the revolution of 1848, and the 23rd of October, the memorial day of the revolution of 1956.
On 20 August the foundation of the state, on 1 May the work is celebrated, on 1 and 2 November we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "shift of working days" has proved itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is finally to be worked out, the Minister of Labour has for a long time been laying down its own regulation.
The legislation applies to all employers and employees, to public employees and public service officials alike.
Only companies and institutions in which the operation is continued without interruption, including on public holidays, are excluded.
This year the working order is only mixed up by the holidays at the end of the year: from 24 December, life in this country will remain formal, since most of the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve take time compensation, or the special holiday for which it has been suspended.
In the next year, more holidays fall into the middle of the week, or the end of the week, so that there will be less redisposing in the working days than this year.
The calendar is first "upside down" around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days.
Saturday, April 26 will be a working day so that Friday, May 2 can be a rest day.
The second redisposing is related to the holiday on 23 October: on Saturday, 18 October you will have to work on Friday, 24 October in advance.
The end of the year will, however, be completely in the mark of the holidays, after everything is and will remain in place as of December 24, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
