Spectacular repair at the space station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his comrades from the International Space Station (ISS) crew will have taken more than seven hours in space to perform the spectacular repair of a defective solar collector, which is essential for the continuation of the scientific work on the station.
A daring exit, which has achieved several records due to its duration, the removal of habitable modules, the speed with which it was organized, and the tools made by the astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem occurred on Wednesday, when the astronauts had unloaded the Harmony module from the Space Shuttle Discovery, a large cylindrical part, which is to soon record the European and Japanese scientific laboratories.
This module is a kind of landing bridge for the module laboratories.
But you have to be able to supply them with electricity.
The second task of the crew was to implement a 17.5 tonnes power generation module via solar panels already located on the ISS in order to put it in its final position.
After she had moved it, the crew moved on to the restructuring of the solar panels of the module, the span of which is 76 meters.
And it happened that one of the collectors, which can be seen as accordion, was damaged by a clamped cable on a length of about one meter.
The restructuring was stopped in order not to damage the collector any more.
The astronauts, who were originally to leave the space ferry Discovery for a control course and then repair another solar collector whose rotation system was flawed, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was chosen to walk around at the end of the 30-metre long remote-controlled arm of the space ferry, which had been attached to the station, to do the repair.
He is one of NASA's best space walkers.
Large, durable, very clever, he has a well-developed upper body and long arms.
The 46-year-old trained doctor was therefore chosen to operate the injured solar collector.
After having carefully examined the damage, he separated the faulty cable and fixed a kind of rail on the damaged site.
He was supported by a second space walker, who remained near the lock, and, from inside, by the other astronauts, among them Peggy Whitson, commander of the crew.
The tool he used, a mini-hockey bat, wrapped with an isolator to prevent an electric blow on the solar collectors that generate several hundred volts, the astronauts had thought and made on board the station.
When the action was over, Scott Parazynski waited until the collector was fully folded before he counted his tools and returned to the station.
Last afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed half a day of relaxation before seven astronauts returned today to the space ferry Discovery to take the return flight to Earth on Wednesday.
