A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are located on a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, could not be seen until now, unless with a humanitarian intention, that is, individual and name-related, that is, on request of a former victim or his family.
In May 2006, the eleven states, including Germany, France, Israel and the US, agreed to make them available to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to carry out research, in particular on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of concentration camps and the health of forced workers, explains Reto Master, head of these archives, which are managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several countries, including Germany, have been opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public because of the delicate nature of certain information.
Like, for example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some of the victims of deportation.
The inmate lists of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been brought together after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen more than 300 permanent employees are working on tens of thousands of personal requests.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
There is nothing fundamentally new to be expected in these documents, Pr. Wolfgang Benz, head of the research centre for anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, explained in 2006.
