New concerns about gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk of Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe being affected.
Most of the Russian exports of natural gas to the European Union (EU) are led by Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is observed very closely.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge higher transit charges from Russia.
A previous conflict between the two countries last year reduced supplies to the EU countries.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow is happening at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian, state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine must pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine has to be more calculated, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% in addition for natural gas from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine must pay 40% more for imports of Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important host countries in talks," said the economic minister of Ukraine Anatoli Kinakh of the Reuters news agency.
"The changing prices of natural gas should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments concerning the level of transit charges [to Western Europe] via Ukraine."
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom reduced supplies to Ukraine.
This led to a fall in exports to Western Europe, which dramatically increased prices.
Russian gas is a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
The result is that Gazprom complements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
