Black also expressed concern that the Scottish State Health Service had no precise ideas about the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important controls were carried out correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The main financial controller examined staff recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area following the attack on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a off-road car was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video transmission at Old Bailey in October and was charged with the alleged car bomb attack in the UK.
The State Health Service is expected to carry out controls before the employment of foreign staff to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorization to work in the United Kingdom.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review pre-trial records, the Agency does not have the responsibility to obtain this information outside the UK.
The report of the chief auditor now states, in addition to other recommendations, that the board should take up guidelines of the criminal record, which will help employers to check in different countries.
"Although we have found some evidence of these controls in some staff documents, they have not been carried out routinely."
Black said that the Scottish health authorities would follow their research guidelines to a great extent before the job was done, but added: "Our report shows areas where the system can be improved to ensure that accurate information on the number of foreign health service workers is available."
BMA Scotland Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations in the run-up to the recruitment of potential NHS employees would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report states that current pre-employment tests of the NHS Scotland work well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say that they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of them doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number was likely to be higher, also because the board of directors had problems identifying those employees who were on leave for an indefinite period of time.
The investigation also found that established control procedures by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian have been largely observed.
