These aren't Warhol's boxes.
Those who connect the terms Sweden and the wooden box think of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At present, manufacturing wooden boxes in Sweden are throwing dark shadows on Warhol's work directory.
A large part of the ninety-four listed Brillo boxes of the "Stockholm type" are forgeries.
After a few months ago, the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" has created doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes in 1968, internal research in the Moderna Museet in Stockholm is now a sobering result: the six "Brillo boxes" which the former museum director Pontus Hultén gave to the Moderna Museet in 1995 are copies - and probably the majority of the around one hundred other Brillo boxes of the "type Stockholm" are in the international art market.
The history of the past is encircled, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes," painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard cartons of the "Brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - was made of hundreds of cardboard brillo boxes: these were not from Warhol (for cost reasons), but were delivered directly from the Brillo cartonage factory.
These were not works of art, but their role models, but mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol was probably allowed to produce a few Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden in 1968, but they were not issued in the Moderna Museet.
Time witnesses now speak of about fifteen cases, which at that time have rightly entered the art and auction history as an authorized original Andy-Warhol-Brillo-Boxes called "type Stockholm."
Some of them have achieved more than $100 000 at auctions.
The problem is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that there were about a hundred wooden boxes produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol had left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were only produced in 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol was already dead for three years.
Lars Bystrom, the chief conservator at the Moderna Museet, has also examined three of the Swedish private-owned brillo boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press panels were first grunded and grilled, and then white oil was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, suggests that the colour was applied directly to the press panel with a paint roll without a primer - and it is not oil, but acrylic.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," says the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve, saying: "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in his collection as copies / exhibition material."
In July, however, the Authentication Board announced that it would follow up the "serious accusations" raised in the matter of the soap powder boxes.
But ever since then, you have been hiding in relentless silence.
